====Verb====
{{en-verb|es}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To strike with a lash; to whip or scourge with a lash, or with something like one.
#* {{RQ:Dryden Satire|1}}
#*: We '''lash''' the pupil, and defraud the ward
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To strike forcibly and quickly, as with a lash; to beat, or beat upon, with a motion like that of a lash.
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 29, 2010| author=Chris Whyatt| title=Chelsea 1 - 0 Bolton| work=BBC| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9309542.stm| passage={{w|Carlo Ancelotti}}'s out-of-sorts team struggled to hit the target in the first half as {{w|Bolton Wanderers|Bolton}} threatened with Matthew Taylor '''lashing''' just wide.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To throw out with a jerk or quickly.
#* {{RQ:Dryden Meta}}
#*: He falls, and '''lashing''' up his heels, his rider throws.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To scold; or to satirize; to censure with severity.
#: {{syn|en|berate}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To ply the whip; to strike.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To utter censure or sarcastic language.
#* {{RQ:Dryden Satire|5}}
#*: To laugh at follies, or to '''lash''' at vice.
# {{lb|en|intransitive|of rain}} To fall heavily, especially in the phrase ''[[lash down]]''
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=October 1, 2011| author=Tom Fordyce| title=Rugby World Cup 2011: England 16-12 Scotland| work=BBC Sport| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/15124512.stm| passage=With rain '''lashing''' across the ground at kick-off and every man in Auckland seemingly either English-born or supporting Scotland, Eden Park was transformed into Murrayfield in March.}}

